c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.0dd5f59a-ab21-4b14-88f6-5f8acdf20aea.prompt=Alternate Credentials - Password\: c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.0f6e857e-a4d2-45c0-b910-b16523509330.description=
Retrieves the requested Windows Performance Counter Value.  Takes 5 samples in 1 second intervals and returns the average.

Input Parameters\:
host - Hostname or ip address of the target machine.
object - Tthe counter object (ex. Processor).
counter - The counter's name (ex. % Processor Time).
instance - The instance of the counter (if applicable) (ex. _Total).
user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation (can be left blank).
password - Password of the user.

Responses\:
success - Retrieved the counter successfully.
failure - Failed to retrieve the counter.

Extra Results\:
VALUE - The actual value captured.

Notes\:
This operation checks the value of a performance counter that must be running on the target windows host prior to flow execution\:
Performance Object\: memory
Performance Counter\: available mbytes
This performance counter can be enabled using PerfMon.exe on the target host.
c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.11036c25-e60c-4c83-9d0d-101c1e88dcdc.prompt=Please enter target hostname\: c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.1e7ecbc8-c580-4082-8ae6-dbbd59251c69.prompt=Alternate Credentials - UserName\: c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.22c9f1f2-a10e-4dbe-a86f-a20dda3e8b95.prompt=Alternate Credentials - UserName\: c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.23dcfd5a-2a1c-4a59-a595-5ab92223964e.prompt=HostName\: c8a187b3-687e-4cf1-ab5c-0b2ad8c26aef.23ea073e-a537-47c4-8275-edfe439156e3.description=

Displays a message to the user.

Inputs\:
  message - The message text to display
  title - The title on the message window. Defaults to "Status message".

Responses\:
  Always returns success.

Examples\:
  In order to display the message "Finished" to the user, go to the 
  detail screen for the input named "message" and change the Otherwise option
  from Prompt User to Use Constant.  Then enter the text "Finished" into the
  Constant Value field.

  References to flow variables in the Contant Value field are expanded so that
  the text may be dynamic.  Flow variable references are of the form
  ${variable}.  For example, the text\:
     ${count} systems were modified 
  could be used to display a message about the number of systems that were
  repaired, whose value is in the flow variable "count".

  When the message is displayed, it will properly render any embedded html
  tags, which permits creating messages with more advanced formatting.  For 
  example to display a message in italics you could use\:
    This is important
  or to display a message in red\:
    This is really  important

  You can create messages that contain multiple lines by entering a multiple
  line message in the Constant Value field, or by using HTML 
 tags for line
  breaks.  Note that \n characters are displayed literally and are not used for
  creating multiple lines.
